      },
      "date": "2012-08-14 22:09:47.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(12 inline comments)\n\nIt looks like the patch id not apply to the kernel so the build failed.  Possibly it is based on a different kernel than the latest?  See lustre/ChangeLog for the currently-supported kernel.\n\n patch -p1 -F1 -s\n 3 out of 12 hunks FAILED -- saving rejects to file drivers/md/raid5.c.rej\n 1 out of 2 hunks FAILED -- saving rejects to file drivers/md/raid5.h.rej\n 7 out of 19 hunks FAILED -- saving rejects to file drivers/md/raid5.c.rej\n 1 out of 1 hunk FAILED -- saving rejects to file drivers/md/raid5.h.rej\n\nSome other style issues that could be improved, as commented inline.  This code isn't really something that I'm familiar with, but I'm assuming that you use it regularly in your appliance, so it is well tested.\n\nAlso, have you tried submitting some or all of these patches to the upstream kernel maintainer recently?  Does it improve the performance or reduce CPU overhead for non-Lustre MD RAID usage?  It would be nice to avoid having to continue to patch the kernel for this code forever.  This isn't a requirement for landing to master, just was wondering if we could get rid of these patches, since we are nearly free of other core kernel patches now and at some point we may stop patching the kernel entirely (only ldiskfs).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
